{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628536"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:57:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:57:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17223"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17223"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9913"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76370"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9913"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17223"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61879"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5864"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23252"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76370"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of headaches. She describes the headaches as dull and persistent, but they significantly worsen when she changes position or performs activities like coughing or straining. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her headaches?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cluster headache","Epidural haematoma","Intracranial mass","Migraine","Tension-type headache"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s headaches are exacerbated by positional changes and Valsalva manoeuvres, which are red flags for increased intracranial pressure. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eintracranial mass\u003C/strong\u003E can cause these symptoms due to mass effect and alteration of cerebrospinal fluid dynamics, leading to increased pressure when the patient changes position.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eepidural haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E presents with an acute onset of symptoms following head trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMigraines\u003C/strong\u003E are usually pulsatile and may be associated with nausea, photophobia, and phonophobia, but they are not worsened by positional changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETension-type headaches\u003C/strong\u003E are described as a band-like pressure around the head and are not influenced by changes in position or Valsalva manoeuvres.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECluster headaches\u003C/strong\u003E are characterised by severe unilateral pain, often around the eye, and are not affected by positional changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Headaches that worsen with positional changes or Valsalva manoeuvres can indicate increased intracranial pressure.","An intracranial mass can cause headaches that are exacerbated by changes in position due to shifts in cerebrospinal fluid dynamics."],"references":["Bigal ME, Lipton RB. The differential diagnosis of chronic daily headaches: an algorithm-based approach. J Headache Pain. 2007 Oct;8(5):263-72. doi: 10.1007/s10194-007-0418-3. Epub 2007 Oct 23. PMID: 17955166; PMCID: PMC2793374","Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012 Aug;6(3):124-32. doi: 10.1177/2049463712459691. PMID: 26516483; PMCID: PMC4590146","Mart\u00ednez Barbero JP, L\u00e1inez Ramos-Bossini AJ, Rivera-Izquierdo M, Sendra-Portero F, Ben\u00edtez-S\u00e1nchez JM, Cervilla JA. Prevalence and Risk Factors Associated with Tumors and Other Structural Anomalies in Brain MRI Performed to Rule out Secondary Headache: A Multicenter Observational Study. Int J Environ Res Public Health. 2022 Mar 16;19(6):3521. doi: 10.3390/ijerph19063521. PMID: 35329206; PMCID: PMC8956087.","Hadidchi S, Surento W, Lerner A, Liu CJ, Gibbs WN, Kim PE, Shiroishi MS. Headache and Brain Tumor. Neuroimaging Clin N Am. 2019 May;29(2):291-300. doi: 10.1016/j.nic.2019.01.008. Epub 2019 Feb 20. PMID: 30926118.","Palmieri A, Valentinis L, Zanchin G. Update on headache and brain tumors. Cephalalgia. 2021 Apr;41(4):431-437. doi: 10.1177/0333102420974351. Epub 2020 Nov 28. PMID: 33249916."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61879"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17223"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61879"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T09:49:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T09:50:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9913"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76370"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHead